Profitability Ratios

    ROE: -191.1%
 
Return on Equity (ROE) of -191.1% suggests that a company may not be able to fund future growth from within.

    ROS: -4,663.0%
 
The value of Return on Sales depends on the business and/or industry. Usually the higher ratio the better.

    ROA: -146.6%
 
Return on Assets (ROA). Low ratio usually means poor performance, or ineffective use of assets by management. High ratio usually means good performance.

    ROI: -242.1%
 
Return on Investment (ROI) of -242.1% suggests that a company may not be able to fund future growth from within.

    ROIC: -191.1%
 
Return on Invested Capital (ROIC) of -191.1% suggests that a company may not be able to fund future growth from within.




Liquidity Ratios

    Current Ratio: 2.54
 
Current Ratio of 2.54 suggests that money that could be working for the business is tied up in government securities, cash savings or other safe funds.

    Quick Ratio: 1.99
 
Quick Ratio of 1.99 suggests that a company is doing well.

    Cash Turnover: 0.10
 
Turnover Of Cash Ratio of 0.10 suggests that a company may have funds tied up in short-term low-yielding assets or may have a cash surplus, which is not invested in the business.

    Debt/Equity: 65.1%
 
Debt to Equity Ratio of 65.1% suggests that a company is doing well.

    Debt/FCF: 0.00
 
Debt/FCF of 0.00 suggests that a company has a negative Free Cash Flow and probably will not be able to pay off its long term debt.


Efficiency Ratios

    Avg Collection Period: 30.34
 
Average Collection Period of 30.34 days suggests that a company is doing well.

    Inventory Turnover: 1.89
 
Inventory Turnover Ratio of 1.89 suggests a large inventory, a never-out-of-stock situation, perhaps some obsolete items, or it could indicate poor liquidity and possible overstocking of items.

    Profit Margin: -4,937.7%
 







